            "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/25169297/numpy-logarithm-with-base-n",
            "title": "NumPy: Logarithm with base n",
            "body": "<p>From the <a href=\"http://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/reference/routines.math.html#exponents-and-logarithms\" rel=\"noreferrer\">numpy documentation on logarithms</a>, I have found functions to take the logarithm with base <a href=\"http://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/reference/generated/numpy.log.html#numpy.log\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><em>e</em></a>, <a href=\"http://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/reference/generated/numpy.log2.html#numpy.log2\" rel=\"noreferrer\">2</a>, and <a href=\"http://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/reference/generated/numpy.log10.html#numpy.log10\" rel=\"noreferrer\">10</a>:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-py prettyprint-override\"><code>import numpy as np\nnp.log(np.e**3) #3.0\nnp.log2(2**3)   #3.0\nnp.log10(10**3) #3.0\n</code></pre>\n<p>However, how do I take the logarithm with base <em>n</em> (e.g. 42) in numpy?</p>\n"
